>
  <p>
    Most systems work beautifully on your most organized day. Memoato is designed for the other days: when attention
    is elsewhere, energy is low, or opening the “right” app already feels like too much work.
  </p>

  <h2>Friction is the real feature</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Write naturally</strong> — no need to translate a thought into a form before saving it.</li>
    <li><strong>One place to begin</strong> — a quick raw log can hold numbers, context, feelings, and events together.</li>
    <li><strong>Fewer decisions</strong> — learned defaults and existing categories reduce repetitive choices.</li>
    <li><strong>Fast feedback</strong> — the timeline and views make recent life easy to scan.</li>
    <li><strong>No broken streak</strong> — leave for a week, return with one sentence, and continue.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Messy input is valid input</h2>
  <p>
    A useful memory might be `low energy, skipped gym, walked after lunch`. It might be `89.8 kg`. It might be a detail
    about a purchase, a person, or a place. Memoato preserves the original note and organizes only what is genuinely
    helpful.
  </p>

  <h2>Privacy reduces another kind of friction</h2>
  <p>
    People will not write honestly in a system that feels unsafe. Memoato offers cloud sync, encrypted cloud, and
    local-only modes so you can choose the trade-off that lets you actually use it. Read the details in the
    <a href="/privacy">privacy policy</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is a product design perspective, not medical advice. Different brains need different tools; Memoato simply
    tries to make remembering require less executive function.
  </p>

